{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "SoilHydraulicProperties",
        "description": "Soil hydraulic properties for an urban-canopy pervious-road soil column following Section 5.3.1 of Oleson et al. (2010, CLM4 Tech Note). Computes five Clapp-Hornberger / Cosby-style properties from the soil sand and clay fractions and the local volumetric water content: saturated hydraulic conductivity k_sat (Eq. 5.70), porosity θ_sat (Eq. 5.71), Clapp-Hornberger exponent B (Eq. 5.72), saturated matric potential ψ_sat (Eq. 5.74), and matric potential ψ (Eq. 5.73, clamped on both sides). Migrated from UrbanCanopy.jl@9200edd4 src/hydrology.jl:322 (`SoilHydraulicProperties` @component). Observed-only: all three inputs are parameters and all five outputs are given by single algebraic equations.",
        "tags": [
            "urban_canopy",
            "hydrology",
            "soil",
            "clapp-hornberger",
            "cosby",
            "observed-only",
            "clmu"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-12T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "UrbanCanopy.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-nvfe)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Oleson, K. W., et al. (2010). Technical Description of version 4.0 of the Community Land Model (CLM). NCAR Technical Note NCAR/TN-478+STR. Chapter 5 (Soil Water), Section 5.3.1 (Hydraulic Properties), Eqs. 5.69-5.74, p. 131."
            },
            {
                "citation": "Clapp, R. B., and G. M. Hornberger (1978). Empirical equations for some soil hydraulic properties. Water Resources Research, 14(4), 601-604."
            },
            {
                "citation": "Cosby, B. J., G. M. Hornberger, R. B. Clapp, and T. R. Ginn (1984). A statistical exploration of the relationships of soil moisture characteristics to the physical properties of soils. Water Resources Research, 20(6), 682-690."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "SoilHydraulicProperties": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: UrbanCanopy.jl@9200edd4f15609f20339d3a7d104de8064544310:src/hydrology.jl:322\nUpstream `SoilHydraulicProperties` is an MTK `@component` whose three inputs (pct_sand, pct_clay, θ_i) are `@parameters` and whose five outputs (k_sat, θ_sat, B, ψ_sat, ψ) are time-indexed `@variables` with five algebraic equations (no derivatives). Identical structure preserved here.\n\nUnicode parameter / variable names θ_i, θ_sat, ψ_sat, ψ are preserved from upstream — sibling files in this directory (soil_water_flux.esm, water_table_depth.esm, interface_hydraulic_conductivity.esm, soil_water_content_calc.esm) already established that unicode identifiers are the rig convention for new urban_canopy migrations and the canonical Python runner accepts them.\n\nThe upstream component declares three `@constants` (k_coeff, ψ_coeff, ψ_min); they are encoded here as parameters with the upstream default values, mirroring the convention used by sibling files (groundwater_drainage.esm, surface_runoff_infiltration.esm) for `@constants`-to-parameter promotion. Default values: k_coeff = 7.0556e-6 m/s (paper's 0.0070556 mm/s converted to m/s, Eq. 5.70), ψ_coeff = -0.010 m (paper's -10.0 mm converted to m, Eq. 5.74), ψ_min = -1.0e5 m (paper's -1e8 mm converted to m). The mm-to-m conversions are applied at the @constants declaration site upstream; this file inherits the SI values so its outputs are SI-consistent without further conversion.\n\nEq. 5.73 (matric potential) carries two clamps on the water-content ratio (θ_i / θ_sat) to keep ψ finite: an inner `max(θ_i, 0.01 * θ_sat)` floor on the numerator keeps the ratio ≥ 0.01 (prevents division-by-zero and excessive negative exponents as the soil approaches dryness), and an outer `max(..., ψ_min)` floor on ψ itself keeps it ≥ -1e5 m even when the inner clamp's value still produces an absurdly negative matric potential (e.g. at very high B for clay-rich soils). Both clamps are preserved verbatim from upstream Eq. 5.73 — they are physical regularizers, not numerical hacks, and the canonical Python runner reproduces the upstream Julia results to machine precision when both clamps fire.\n\nObservability classification: this component is functionally observed-only — all five output variables are given by single algebraic equations in terms of the parameters (the `(t)` time index has no role since there is no derivative). Test scenarios use `time_span: [0, 1]` and sample at t=0 to mirror the convention used by the other observed-only ESM files in this directory (soil_water_flux.esm, water_table_depth.esm, groundwater_drainage.esm, interface_hydraulic_conductivity.esm).\n\nDefault parameter values: pct_sand = 50 %, pct_clay = 20 %, θ_i = 0.3 m^3/m^3 — a typical CLMU loam at partial saturation (θ_i ≈ 0.7 × θ_sat). The qualitative-test scenarios in the upstream `SoilHydraulicProperties - Qualitative Behavior` testitem (UrbanCanopy.jl test/hydrology_test.jl:970) use the same pct_clay = 20, θ_i = 0.3 baseline.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-9): observed-only algebraic system (no ODE integration); the five equations involve O(10) IEEE-754 float64 operations each, with k_sat and ψ_sat carrying one `^` (10.0^x) call (≈1 ULP of relative error) and ψ carrying one `^` plus two `max` calls — worst-case roundoff is ~10*ULP ≈ 1e-15. 1e-9 leaves comfortable headroom and is well below any plausible physical-discrimination scale on soil hydraulic properties (k_sat ∈ [1e-7, 1e-4] m/s across realistic Cosby sand fractions; θ_sat ∈ [0.4, 0.49]; B ∈ [3, 11]; ψ_sat ∈ [-0.8, -0.07] m). Tests that pin upstream test:466's `≈ rtol=1e-6` assertions use the looser `rel: 1e-6` tolerance from the upstream to confirm cross-runner consistency."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1.0e-9
            },
            "variables": {
                "pct_sand": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 50.0,
                    "description": "Percent sand content of the soil layer (dimensionless mass percent, 0-100)"
                },
                "pct_clay": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 20.0,
                    "description": "Percent clay content of the soil layer (dimensionless mass percent, 0-100)"
                },
                "θ_i": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/m^3",
                    "default": 0.3,
                    "description": "Total volumetric soil water content of the layer (Oleson Eq. 5.73 input)"
                },
                "k_coeff": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m/s",
                    "default": 7.0556e-6,
                    "description": "Coefficient for saturated hydraulic conductivity (Oleson Eq. 5.70, converted from 0.0070556 mm/s to 7.0556e-6 m/s)"
                },
                "ψ_coeff": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": -0.010,
                    "description": "Coefficient for saturated matric potential (Oleson Eq. 5.74, converted from -10.0 mm to -0.010 m)"
                },
                "ψ_min": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": -1.0e5,
                    "description": "Minimum (most-negative) soil matric potential (Oleson Eq. 5.73 outer clamp, converted from -1e8 mm to -1e5 m)"
                },
                "k_sat": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m/s",
                    "description": "Saturated hydraulic conductivity (Oleson Eq. 5.70)"
                },
                "θ_sat": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^3/m^3",
                    "description": "Volumetric water content at saturation / porosity (Oleson Eq. 5.71)"
                },
                "B": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Clapp-Hornberger exponent (Oleson Eq. 5.72, dimensionless)"
                },
                "ψ_sat": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m",
                    "description": "Saturated soil matric potential (Oleson Eq. 5.74)"
                },
                "ψ": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m",
                    "description": "Soil matric potential (Oleson Eq. 5.73, clamped: inner θ_i/θ_sat ratio ≥ 0.01, outer ψ ≥ ψ_min)"
                }
            },
            "equations": [
                {
                    "lhs": "k_sat",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "*",
                        "args": [
                            "k_coeff",
                            {
                                "op": "^",
                                "args": [
                                    10.0,
                                    {
                                        "op": "+",
                                        "args": [
                                            -0.884,
                                            { "op": "*", "args": [0.0153, "pct_sand"] }
                                        ]
                                    }
                                ]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "lhs": "θ_sat",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "-",
                        "args": [
                            0.489,
                            { "op": "*", "args": [0.00126, "pct_sand"] }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "lhs": "B",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "+",
                        "args": [
                            2.91,
                            { "op": "*", "args": [0.159, "pct_clay"] }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "lhs": "ψ_sat",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "*",
                        "args": [
                            "ψ_coeff",
                            {
                                "op": "^",
                                "args": [
                                    10.0,
                                    {
                                        "op": "-",
                                        "args": [
                                            1.88,
                                            { "op": "*", "args": [0.0131, "pct_sand"] }
                                        ]
                                    }
                                ]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "lhs": "ψ",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "max",
                        "args": [
                            {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": [
                                    "ψ_sat",
                                    {
                                        "op": "^",
                                        "args": [
                                            {
                                                "op": "/",
                                                "args": [
                                                    {
                                                        "op": "max",
                                                        "args": [
                                                            "θ_i",
                                                            { "op": "*", "args": [0.01, "θ_sat"] }
                                                        ]
                                                    },
                                                    "θ_sat"
                                                ]
                                            },
                                            { "op": "*", "args": [-1, "B"] }
                                        ]
                                    }
                                ]
                            },
                            "ψ_min"
                        ]
                    }
                }
            ],
            "tests": [
                {
                    "id": "eq_verify_saturated",
                    "description": "Reproduces upstream Equation Verification fixture (UrbanCanopy.jl test/hydrology_test.jl:466) with pct_sand = 50, pct_clay = 20, θ_i = θ_sat. Anchors all five outputs against the Cosby/Clapp-Hornberger closed-form values for a mid-range loam: k_sat = 0.0070556e-3 * 10^(-0.884 + 0.0153 * 50) ≈ 5.365e-6 m/s; θ_sat = 0.489 - 0.00126*50 = 0.426 m^3/m^3; B = 2.91 + 0.159*20 = 6.09; ψ_sat = -0.010 * 10^(1.88 - 0.0131*50) ≈ -0.16788 m. At saturation θ_i = θ_sat the ratio is exactly 1 so ψ = ψ_sat — a key invariant of Eq. 5.73. Tolerances loosened to rel = 1e-6 here to match the upstream Julia test's pinned tolerance and confirm cross-runner consistency (the Python runner reproduces the Julia closed-form to ≈1 ULP, far tighter than 1e-6).",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "pct_sand": 50.0,
                        "pct_clay": 20.0,
                        "θ_i": 0.426
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "k_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": 5.364558079579147e-06, "tolerance": { "rel": 1.0e-6 } },
                        { "variable": "θ_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.426, "tolerance": { "rel": 1.0e-6 } },
                        { "variable": "B",     "time": 0.0, "expected": 6.09, "tolerance": { "rel": 1.0e-6 } },
                        { "variable": "ψ_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": -0.16788040181225597, "tolerance": { "rel": 1.0e-6 } },
                        { "variable": "ψ",     "time": 0.0, "expected": -0.16788040181225597, "tolerance": { "rel": 1.0e-4 } }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "typical_partial_saturation",
                    "description": "Realistic CLMU operating point: pct_sand = 50, pct_clay = 20, θ_i = 0.3 m^3/m^3 (partial saturation, θ_i / θ_sat ≈ 0.7042). k_sat, θ_sat, B, ψ_sat are identical to the eq_verify_saturated case (they depend only on pct_sand and pct_clay), but ψ now reflects the partial-saturation matric potential: ψ = ψ_sat * (0.3/0.426)^(-6.09) ≈ -0.16788 * 8.4768 ≈ -1.42048 m. Neither clamp fires. Anchors the non-equilibrium branch of Eq. 5.73 — the dominant operating regime for the urban-canopy soil column.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "pct_sand": 50.0,
                        "pct_clay": 20.0,
                        "θ_i": 0.3
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "k_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": 5.364558079579147e-06 },
                        { "variable": "θ_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.426 },
                        { "variable": "B",     "time": 0.0, "expected": 6.09 },
                        { "variable": "ψ_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": -0.16788040181225597 },
                        { "variable": "ψ",     "time": 0.0, "expected": -1.420482923905238 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "sandy_low_clay_dry",
                    "description": "Sandy soil with low clay at moderate-to-dry water content: pct_sand = 70, pct_clay = 10, θ_i = 0.15 m^3/m^3. Tests Eq. 5.70-5.74 in the sandy / less-clayey regime: k_sat increases with sand (≈1.085e-5 m/s, ~2× the default loam), θ_sat decreases (0.4008 m^3/m^3), B decreases with clay (4.5), ψ_sat is less negative for sandy soils (≈-0.0918 m). With θ_i / θ_sat ≈ 0.374 and B = 4.5, the (-B) exponent drives ψ to ≈ -7.65 m — moderately dry but well above the ψ_min clamp.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "pct_sand": 70.0,
                        "pct_clay": 10.0,
                        "θ_i": 0.15
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "k_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.0852603880122091e-05 },
                        { "variable": "θ_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.4008 },
                        { "variable": "B",     "time": 0.0, "expected": 4.5 },
                        { "variable": "ψ_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": -0.09183325964835806 },
                        { "variable": "ψ",     "time": 0.0, "expected": -7.651807612176636 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "clayey_partial",
                    "description": "Clay-rich soil at partial saturation: pct_sand = 10, pct_clay = 50, θ_i = 0.3 m^3/m^3. Tests Eq. 5.70-5.74 in the clayey regime — low sand suppresses k_sat (≈1.31e-6 m/s, ~4× lower than the default loam), high clay increases B sharply (10.86 vs 6.09), and ψ_sat is significantly more negative (-0.561 m vs -0.168 m for the default loam). The large B = 10.86 amplifies the (θ_i / θ_sat)^(-B) factor: ψ ≈ -85.16 m — high-clay soils retain water more tightly. Still well above the ψ_min = -1e5 m clamp.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "pct_sand": 10.0,
                        "pct_clay": 50.0,
                        "θ_i": 0.3
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "k_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.3107925113344989e-06 },
                        { "variable": "θ_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.4764 },
                        { "variable": "B",     "time": 0.0, "expected": 10.86 },
                        { "variable": "ψ_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": -0.5610479760324704 },
                        { "variable": "ψ",     "time": 0.0, "expected": -85.1601483413643 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "inner_clamp_fires_only",
                    "description": "Very dry soil where the inner `max(θ_i, 0.01 * θ_sat)` clamp on the ratio fires, but the outer ψ_min clamp does NOT — isolates the inner-clamp branch of Eq. 5.73. pct_sand = 80, pct_clay = 0 (extreme: low B = 2.91), θ_i = 0.001 m^3/m^3. 0.01 * θ_sat = 0.01 * 0.3882 = 0.003882 > θ_i = 0.001, so the ratio is pinned at 0.01. (0.01)^(-2.91) = 100^2.91 = 10^5.82 ≈ 6.607e5. ψ = -0.0679 * 6.607e5 ≈ -44874.54 m, which is more negative than the typical operating range but still > ψ_min = -1e5, so the outer clamp does not engage. Verifies that the inner clamp protects against extreme dryness without prematurely triggering the outer clamp.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "pct_sand": 80.0,
                        "pct_clay": 0.0,
                        "θ_i": 0.001
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "k_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.5435970913938464e-05 },
                        { "variable": "θ_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.3882 },
                        { "variable": "B",     "time": 0.0, "expected": 2.91 },
                        { "variable": "ψ_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": -0.06792036326171844 },
                        { "variable": "ψ",     "time": 0.0, "expected": -44874.53899331323 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "both_clamps_fire",
                    "description": "Extreme dry state where BOTH clamps in Eq. 5.73 fire: pct_sand = 50, pct_clay = 20, θ_i = 0.001 m^3/m^3. 0.01 * θ_sat = 0.00426 > θ_i = 0.001 so the inner clamp pins the ratio at 0.01. (0.01)^(-6.09) = 100^6.09 = 10^12.18 ≈ 1.514e12. ψ_sat * ratio^(-B) ≈ -0.168 * 1.514e12 ≈ -2.541e11 m — far below ψ_min = -1e5. The outer clamp engages and pins ψ at exactly ψ_min = -1.0e5 m. Verifies the outer-clamp branch and confirms that the IEEE-754 result hits ψ_min exactly (abs = 1e-15 floor).",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "pct_sand": 50.0,
                        "pct_clay": 20.0,
                        "θ_i": 0.001
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "k_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": 5.364558079579147e-06 },
                        { "variable": "θ_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.426 },
                        { "variable": "B",     "time": 0.0, "expected": 6.09 },
                        { "variable": "ψ_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": -0.16788040181225597 },
                        { "variable": "ψ",     "time": 0.0, "expected": -100000.0, "tolerance": { "abs": 1.0e-10 } }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "qual_low_sand_ksat",
                    "description": "Lower-sand monotonicity-check anchor for the upstream `SoilHydraulicProperties - Qualitative Behavior` testitem (UrbanCanopy.jl test/hydrology_test.jl:982): higher sand content should produce higher k_sat (Eq. 5.70's 10^(0.0153 * pct_sand) factor is monotone-increasing in pct_sand). At pct_sand = 20, pct_clay = 20, θ_i = 0.3: k_sat ≈ 1.864e-6 m/s, θ_sat = 0.4638 m^3/m^3 (higher porosity for clay-rich soils, consistent with Eq. 5.71's negative sand-dependence), ψ_sat ≈ -0.415 m (more negative, also consistent with Eq. 5.74). Pairs with qual_high_sand_ksat to verify the k_sat / θ_sat / ψ_sat sand-dependence directions.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "pct_sand": 20.0,
                        "pct_clay": 20.0,
                        "θ_i": 0.3
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "k_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.8643779228160723e-06 },
                        { "variable": "θ_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.4638 },
                        { "variable": "B",     "time": 0.0, "expected": 6.09 },
                        { "variable": "ψ_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": -0.41495404263436286 },
                        { "variable": "ψ",     "time": 0.0, "expected": -5.892312769696793 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "qual_high_sand_ksat",
                    "description": "Higher-sand monotonicity-check companion to qual_low_sand_ksat: at pct_sand = 80 (other parameters held: pct_clay = 20, θ_i = 0.3), k_sat ≈ 1.544e-5 m/s — about 8.3× larger than the pct_sand = 20 value, confirming Eq. 5.70's strong sand-dependence (decade per ~65 % sand). θ_sat drops to 0.3882 m^3/m^3 (lower porosity in sandy soils) and ψ_sat rises to ≈ -0.0679 m (less negative — sandy soils are less retentive). B = 6.09 is unchanged since it depends only on clay. ψ ≈ -0.326 m — less negative than the loam at the same θ_i / θ_sat because the higher θ_sat-relative ratio (0.3 / 0.3882 ≈ 0.773) keeps the (-B)-power factor closer to 1.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "pct_sand": 80.0,
                        "pct_clay": 20.0,
                        "θ_i": 0.3
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "k_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.5435970913938464e-05 },
                        { "variable": "θ_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.3882 },
                        { "variable": "B",     "time": 0.0, "expected": 6.09 },
                        { "variable": "ψ_sat", "time": 0.0, "expected": -0.06792036326171844 },
                        { "variable": "ψ",     "time": 0.0, "expected": -0.3263470887762197 }
                    ]
                }
            ],
            "examples": [
                {
                    "id": "k_sat_vs_pct_sand",
                    "description": "Saturated hydraulic conductivity k_sat vs. percent sand content (Eq. 5.70). Sweeping pct_sand from 5 % (clay-rich) to 95 % (nearly-pure sand) traces the canonical Cosby-style log-linear relationship — k_sat increases by ~1.5 decades over the realistic 5-95 % sand range. The y-axis is logarithmic because Eq. 5.70 places pct_sand inside a 10^(0.0153 * pct_sand) factor.",
                    "initial_state": {
                        "type": "per_variable",
                        "values": {}
                    },
                    "parameters": {
                        "pct_clay": 20.0,
                        "θ_i": 0.3
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "pct_sand",
                                "range": { "start": 5.0, "stop": 95.0, "count": 19, "scale": "linear" }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "k_sat_curve",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "k_sat vs pct_sand: log-linear increase from Eq. 5.70's 10^(0.0153 * pct_sand) factor.",
                            "x": { "variable": "pct_sand", "label": "pct_sand (%)" },
                            "y": { "variable": "k_sat",    "label": "k_sat (m/s)" }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "psi_retention_curve",
                    "description": "Soil-water retention curve: matric potential ψ vs. volumetric water content θ_i for a typical Cosby loam (pct_sand = 50, pct_clay = 20). Sweeps θ_i from 0.05 (very dry) to 0.426 (saturated, θ_sat). Reproduces the canonical Clapp-Hornberger retention curve of Eq. 5.73 — ψ saturates at ψ_sat ≈ -0.168 m near saturation and decreases rapidly toward the inner-clamp regime as θ_i → 0. The y-axis spans many decades so a log-scale view is most informative.",
                    "initial_state": {
                        "type": "per_variable",
                        "values": {}
                    },
                    "parameters": {
                        "pct_sand": 50.0,
                        "pct_clay": 20.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "θ_i",
                                "range": { "start": 0.05, "stop": 0.426, "count": 30, "scale": "linear" }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "psi_curve",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "ψ vs θ_i (Cosby loam, pct_sand=50, pct_clay=20) — the Clapp-Hornberger retention curve of Eq. 5.73.",
                            "x": { "variable": "θ_i", "label": "θ_i (m^3/m^3)" },
                            "y": { "variable": "ψ",   "label": "ψ (m, more negative = drier)" }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "psi_vs_sand_and_clay",
                    "description": "Joint sweep over pct_sand and pct_clay at fixed θ_i = 0.3 m^3/m^3. Surfaces the iso-ψ contours of the soil hydraulic system: ψ depends on all three properties (ψ_sat from sand, B from clay, θ_sat from sand). Clay-rich / low-sand corners exhibit the most negative ψ (high B amplifies the (θ_i / θ_sat)^(-B) factor); high-sand / low-clay corners stay close to ψ_sat (small B, ratio close to 1). The default operating point (sand=50, clay=20) sits in the moderately-negative band.",
                    "initial_state": {
                        "type": "per_variable",
                        "values": {}
                    },
                    "parameters": {
                        "θ_i": 0.3
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "pct_sand",
                                "range": { "start": 10.0, "stop": 90.0, "count": 9, "scale": "linear" }
                            },
                            {
                                "parameter": "pct_clay",
                                "range": { "start": 5.0, "stop": 50.0, "count": 10, "scale": "linear" }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "psi_heatmap",
                            "type": "heatmap",
                            "description": "ψ as a function of sand and clay percentages at θ_i = 0.3 m^3/m^3.",
                            "x": { "variable": "pct_sand", "label": "pct_sand (%)" },
                            "y": { "variable": "pct_clay", "label": "pct_clay (%)" },
                            "value": { "variable": "ψ", "reduce": "final" }
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        }
    }
}
